    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Now, Focus Turns to Constitutional Order; Diminished Office</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Herbert Rosenberg letter opposes suggestion that Congress adopt strong censure resolution against Pres Clinton, incuding a confession that he lied under oath (Dec 20 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You suggest (editorial, Dec. 20) that Congress adopt a strong censure resolution against the President, including a confession that he lied under oath.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You suggest (editorial, Dec. 20) that Congress adopt a strong censure resolution against the President, including a confession that he lied under oath.</p>
        <p>Such a punishment would destroy the authority a President must have. It would leave the country with a disgraced President who would occupy the White House, but be incapable of discharging the duties of his office.</p>
        <p>Removing the President from office would be preferable.</p>
        <p>Serious charges have been leveled against the President. It is unseemly to suggest that he ''cop out.'' If the President is found guilty by the Senate, then he should go. If he is not, then he can rightfully discharge his duties. The country is entitled to no less.</p>
        <p>HERBERT ROSENBERG  Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., Dec. 20, 1998</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
